Project Python Foundations: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Project Created by: Bindu Kaimal

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Reference: Missing Values

The 'rating' column contains 736 instances of the string value 'Not given', but there are no other missing values in the data. To process this column, I will convert it to a numeric data type, and then I will replace all occurrences of 'Not given' with a numeric value. To do so, I will impute the mean rating value for each restaurant's cuisine type, where the mean rating is computed over all restaurants of the same cuisine type as the one being imputed. For example, if a Chinese cuisine restaurant named 'XYZ' has 'Not given' values, I will compute the mean rating value of all other Chinese cuisine restaurants in the data and fill in this mean value for the 'Not given' values of 'XYZ'.

In [44]:
# create a new DataFrame with a new rating column that contains all numeric values
new_df = df.copy()  # make a copy of the original DataFrame

new_df['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(new_df['rating'], errors='coerce')  # convert 'rating' to numeric

# group the DataFrame by 'cuisine_type' and calculate the mean for each group
mean_by_cuisine = new_df.groupby('cuisine_type')['rating'].mean()

# replace 'Not given' values with mean for corresponding 'cuisine_type'
new_df.loc[new_df['rating'].isna(), 'rating'] = new_df.loc[new_df['rating'].isna(), 'cuisine_type'].map(mean_by_cuisine)

# display the new DataFrame
print(new_df)

To calculate the number of bins I used the bins='fd' method specifically refers to the Freedman-Diaconis rule, which calculates the optimal bin width based on the interquartile range (IQR) of the data and the number of observations. This rule can be useful when working with datasets that have non-normal distributions and/or outliers, as it adjusts the bin size to account for the range of values in the data.

Note about: Customer Id & Order Id It is critical to note that Customer Id and Order Id are typically considered as unique identifiers or codes assigned to customers and orders, respectively. These identifiers are generally represented as numerical data, but they do not have any inherent numerical value or meaning in terms of the analysis of the data. Therefore, they are usually treated as nominal or categorical variables rather than numerical variables in statistical analysis. In other words, they are treated as labels or categories rather than quantitative data that can be added, subtracted, or analyzed using arithmetic operations.

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [86]:
# define a function to calculate the revenue generated by the company for each order
def calculate_revenue(cost):
    if cost > 20:
        return cost * 0.75
    elif cost > 5:
        return cost * 0.85
    else:
        return cost

# apply the function to the cost_of_the_order column and sum up the results
net_revenue = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(calculate_revenue).sum()

print('Net revenue generated by the company: ${:.2f}'.format(net_revenue))

Net revenue generated by the company: $25148.52

Observations:¶

The Net Revenue Generated by the company is $25148.52 based on the orders.

This code defines a function called "calculate_revenue" that takes in a parameter "cost" which represents the cost of an order. The function calculates the revenue generated by the company for each order based on the cost of the order. If the cost is greater than 20, the function applies a discount of 25% and returns the discounted cost. If the cost is greater than 5 but less than or equal to 20, the function applies a discount of 15% and returns the discounted cost. If the cost is less than or equal to 5, the function returns the cost as is.

After defining the function, the code applies the function to each value in the "cost_of_the_order" column of a DataFrame called "df". It then sums up the results of the function application to get the net revenue generated by the company.

Finally, the code prints out the net revenue generated by the company in a formatted string with two decimal places.

Question 15: The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered.) [2 marks]¶

In [87]:
# calculate total time taken for each order
df['total_delivery_time'] = df['food_preparation_time'] + df['delivery_time']

# filter orders that take more than 60 minutes
long_delivery_orders = df[df['total_delivery_time'] > 60]['order_id'].nunique()

# calculate percentage of orders that take more than 60 minutes
total_orders = df['order_id'].nunique()
percent_long_delivery = (long_delivery_orders / total_orders) * 100

# print the percentage
print(f"{percent_long_delivery:.2f}% of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered.")

10.54% of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered.

Observations:¶

10.54% of the orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered.

We saw in the multivariate analysis that Spanish cuisine takes longer than 60 minutes on weekdays while Korean food takes shortest time during weekdays and weekends.

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations.) [6 marks]¶

Conclusions:¶

A summary of the results:

Dataset includes 178 restaurants serving 14 different types of cuisines.

More orders are placed during weekends compared to weekdays.

Minimum food preparation time is 20 minutes, maximum is 35 minutes, and mean is 27 minutes. No outliers found.

Minimum delivery time is 15 minutes, mean is 24 minutes, and maximum is 33 minutes.

There are 1200 unique customer IDs and order IDs are unique for the entire dataset.

Maximum cost of an order is $35.41, mean is $16.49, and minimum is $4.47.

Weak correlations are observed among delivery time, food preparation time, and cost of the order.

American cuisine has the most number of orders and restaurants, followed by Japanese and Italian. Vietnamese has the least number of orders and restaurants.

More income is generated during weekends for all cuisine types and American cuisine generates more income during both weekdays and weekends.

Weekday delivery times take longer than weekend delivery times in general. Rating is not affected by delivery or food preparation time, and 736 rows have no rating given.

Blue Ribbon Fried Chicken, Shake Shack, Blue Ribbon Sushi, and The Meatball Shop are eligible for promotional offers.

Net revenue generated by the company is $25148.52 based on the orders.

10.54% of orders take more than 60 minutes to be delivered.

Spanish cuisine takes longer than 60 minutes on weekdays, while Korean food takes the shortest time during weekdays and weekends.

Conclusion

Based on the information provided, the restaurants and food business in this location seem to be diverse in terms of cuisine types offered. American, Japanese, and Italian are the most popular cuisine types, while Vietnamese, Spanish, and French have fewer orders and restaurants.

The average food preparation time is 27 minutes, which seems reasonable for most customers. The maximum delivery time is 33 minutes, which is within a reasonable timeframe as well. However, 10.54% of the orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered, which could be a cause for concern.

It is interesting to note that the delivery time is longer during weekdays than on weekends. This may be because of higher demand during weekdays, or it may be due to traffic or other external factors. It is also noteworthy that different cuisine types have different delivery and preparation times, with Spanish cuisine taking the longest time to deliver during weekdays.

The average cost of an order is 16.49 dollars, with a maximum of $35.41. This suggests that the customers are willing to pay higher prices for quality food and service. It is also worth noting that the rating is not affected by delivery or preparation time, which suggests that customers prioritize quality over speed.

The fact that there are 1200 unique customer IDs suggests that the restaurant business is popular among the locals, and the repeat customers can be rewarded with discounts and other promotional offers. The Net Revenue Generated by the company is $25148.52, which indicates that the business maybe profitable.

In conclusion, the restaurants and food business in this location seem to be diverse and popular among the locals. While there are some areas of concern such as longer delivery times for certain cuisine types, the overall business appears to be profitable and sustainable. We may need more information to conclusively state the profit or loss of business here.

Recommendations:¶

Based on the analysis results, it appears that a large portion of the dataset (736 rows) have no rating given. To improve customer response to ratings, the following recommendations can be considered:

Encourage customers to leave ratings by offering incentives such as discounts or loyalty points.

Make the rating process as simple and user-friendly as possible, with clear instructions and an easy-to-use interface. Example: Likert Scale, Comment Cards.

Provide customers with more information about the rating system, such as how ratings are used and the benefits of leaving feedback.

Follow up with customers who have placed orders but have not left a rating, perhaps by sending a reminder email or message asking for their feedback.

Ensure that the delivery and food preparation times are consistent and accurate, as these factors may influence a customer's decision to leave a rating.

Take customer feedback seriously and use it to improve the overall quality of the service provided. This can help to build trust and loyalty among customers, which may in turn encourage them to leave ratings in the future.

Based on the analysis, here are some recommendations to improve orders for cuisine types other than American:

Offer promotions and discounts for other cuisine types: As American cuisine has the highest number of orders and restaurants; it might be beneficial to offer promotions and discounts for other cuisine types to encourage customers to try different types of food.

Improve marketing for other cuisine types: The data analysis shows that the number of orders for other cuisine types is lower than that of American cuisine. Therefore, it might be useful to invest in marketing campaigns that promote other cuisine types, such as Japanese, Italian, and Vietnamese, to increase awareness and attract more customers.

Expand the menu for other cuisine types: Offering more variety in the menu for other cuisine types might attract customers who are looking for a wider range of options. It can also encourage repeat orders from customers who enjoy the variety.

Improve delivery and food preparation times: Since the delivery time and food preparation time can affect customer satisfaction, it is important to improve the efficiency of these processes for all cuisine types. This can be achieved through better logistics and training of staff. Restaurants can optimize the delivery process by using efficient routes, tracking delivery vehicles, and using real-time traffic information. This can help reduce the delivery time and improve customer satisfaction.

Collect feedback and ratings for other cuisine types: Encouraging customers to provide feedback and ratings for other cuisine types can help identify areas for improvement and understand customer preferences. This information can then be used to make changes to the menu, improve the quality of food, and enhance the overall customer experience.
